    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/30237 added validation to `--listen`. But ctrl-c on `nvim --headless --listen ./hello.sock` does not delete the socket file. So, keeping this issue open.\r\n\r\n- Without `--headless`, the socket file is deleted on exit. But with `--headless`, it's not.\r\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/26053 also makes the case for handling the `killall -9 nvim` case.\r\n\r\n# Plan\r\n\r\nAs requested here and in https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/26053,\r\n\r\n- when trying to start a server specified by `--listen` *or* `serverstart()`:\r\n    - [ref](https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/26053#issuecomment-1813260697) if libuv supports socket state querying, check whether existing socket file is not in the `LISTEN` state and then remove it.\r\n    - alternatively, just try to connect to the existing socket file and remove it if connection was refused.\r\n    - log a message at \"info\" level when this happens.",
